In simple terms, AOP (Aspect-Oriented Programming) is a way to separate "housekeeping" code from your actual "business" code. [1, 2] 
## 1. What is AOP?
Imagine you’re writing a function to transfer money. The Business Logic is just subtracting from Account A and adding to Account B. However, you also need to:

* Log the transaction.
* Check if the user is logged in (Security).
* Handle errors (Transaction management). [3] 

If you put all that inside your function, the business logic gets buried. AOP allows you to "pluck" those repetitive tasks out and run them automatically whenever the main function is called. [4, 5, 6] 
## 2. Why apply AOP in Spring Boot?
Spring Boot uses AOP to keep your code DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) and clean. Instead of manually writing code to open and close database connections in every method, you just tell Spring to do it "around" the method. It reduces boilerplate and makes the app easier to maintain. [7, 8, 9, 10, 11] 
## 3. Why @Transactional includes AOP?
The @Transactional annotation is the most famous example of AOP in action. [12] 

* Without AOP: You’d have to manually write connection.start(), try { ... }, connection.commit(), and connection.rollback().
* With AOP: When Spring sees @Transactional, it creates a "Proxy" (a wrapper) around your method. This proxy handles the start, commit, and rollback logic automatically, so your method only contains the database operations. [13, 14, 15, 16, 17] 

## 4. Real-Time Example: The "Security Guard"
Think of a Bank Teller (your Business Logic).

* The Teller's job: Process a withdrawal.
* The Problem: We need to make sure every customer is verified before they talk to the teller, and we need to log every visit.

The AOP Approach:
Instead of teaching every Teller how to check IDs and write logs, you hire a Security Guard (the Aspect). [18, 19] 

   1. The Guard stands at the door (Pointcut).
   2. Before anyone reaches the teller (Before Advice), the Guard checks their ID.
   3. After the teller finishes (After Advice), the Guard logs the time they left.

